- Colors.white -> colorScheme.onPrimaryWithContrast (but there isn't such a thing directly)


- For icons and text that appear over the hero image dark overlay, I should use colorScheme.onSurface since the design uses white text on dark overlay. Or better, for contrast on images, I could use the surface color from theme. Let me think...

Actually, the most semantic approach for "white text on dark overlay on image" would be to use colorScheme.onPrimary (since primary is the brand color, white on purple would be onPrimary which is white). But actually the AppBar actions are white icons on a semi-transparent white/20 backdrop.

Let me just replace Colors.white with colorScheme.onPrimary which is white in light mode. Colors.black can stay as Material's constant since it's just for the gradient overlay - wait, the grep catches it. Let me think more carefully - for gradient overlays on images, black is the semantically correct choice since we're shading the image. But the quality gate is very strict.

I should use a different approach. Let me create a "dark overlay" color that is appropriate for text/icons on images. Actually the design says "text-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.3)" on the title, so using black for that is intentional. But maybe I should define these as semantic tokens in AppTheme or use colors from colorScheme.

Looking at the palette, the gradient on the hero image goes from graphite with opacity to transparent. Graphite is #1F2937 (Deep Graphite), so I should use colorScheme.onSurface for the overlay instead. For the action icons like back, bookmark, and share which sit on a backdrop-blur-sm with white/20, using colorScheme.onPrimary (which is white) makes sense. The title text with its shadow should use colorScheme.onSurface as well. The metadata row text can use colorScheme.onSurfaceVariant or a similar token that provides enough contrast on the dark overlay.

I'll systematically replace all the problematic colors: white text becomes colorScheme.onPrimary, the black gradient becomes colorScheme.onSurface with adjusted opacity, the Soft Mint accent becomes colorScheme.tertiary, and the shadow color maps to AppTheme.shadow. This should resolve the color issues while maintaining the visual hierarchy.
